Let's do it.  <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A> at: 2/9/03 3:50:32 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 855<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/9/03 3:28 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=23.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/devil.gif" align=absmiddle>  What if a private company claimed an asteroid?</span><hr size=1> You'd have to constantly use the pooper scooper to scrape the Earth First and Greenpeace nuts off the hulls of your vehicles for daring to violate the sacred environment of space.  And UN legal no doubt would be actively threatening the miner's host country to shut down the operation unless the profits were to be distributed equally among all mankind since everything in the cosmos is &quot;collective property&quot; meaning it belongs to a small group of government control freaks who need the money to forward their scheme of the week.  Hopefully though it would set a precendent that would get more companies and people involved in utilizing space.  That's ultimately the way we will have to open up the space frontier.      <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1997<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/9/03 4:23 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=23.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/zaphod3.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What if a private company claimed an asteroid?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>...unless the profits were to be distributed equally among all mankind since everything in the cosmos is &quot;collective property&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
But once it's on the Earth that should no longer apply... right? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 3308<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/10/03 1:33 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=23.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2001/05/images/021011_nuclear.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What if a private company claimed an asteroid?</span><hr size=1> &quot;<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>What if some mining company(for example) took the World completely unawares...</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->&quot;<br>
<br>
Hence the term &quot;unawares&quot;. Anybody who planned to attempt this coup would realise the UN won't stand by and let it happen. It would have to be a surprise operation. I'd find the most suitable third world host for the launch, call the neighbours to inform them of a 'weather satellite' being launched and land the rock elsewhere. Anyplace ownership of minerals and resources has already been claimed by the company. Land the asteroid, which according to John4303 is relatively easy to do, then start mining. Even if radar operators in Hawaii or some place picked out the trace signature of a big asteroid or telescopes identified it weeks in advance it wouldn't matter. It's just one of those unidentified rogue asteroids. Mother nature finally hit us with one but no damage was done. It might in fact spur NASA to get serious about dealing with the threat. However, I doubt it would even be noticed. The last one slipped between the Earth and moon two days before it was spotted. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=scorebird>Scorebird</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/11/03 8:01 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=23.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/Bart-term.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What if a private company claimed an asteroid?</span><hr size=1>  Actually,I think if the company is registered in a country that didn't ratify The Moon Treaty and The Outer Space Treaty. Then they wouldn't have to worry about the UN. That.at least, is what they did in BACK TO THE MOON by Homer H. Hickam, Jr. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=spacedrive@nuclearspace>Spacedrive</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 41<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/11/03 8:38 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=23.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   property rights in space</span><hr size=1> I've read legal analyst's take on the Outer Space Treaty and this treaty bans claims of national sovereignty of bodies in space, but not private ownership. If someone does this, what's the UN going to do? Pass a resolution? Oh yeah, that'll stop us in our tracks.<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
When we get to the point of real assets on the moon and other places, we will either ignore silly UN treaties or pull out of the treaty alltogether. The UN may not even be around in five years at the rate it's going anyway. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=captainbeowulf>CaptainBeowulf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 15<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/17/03 10:04 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=23.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   UN and asteroid defence</span><hr size=1> The UN ban on space-based nuclear weapons actually becomes silly as well, when considered in terms of asteroid defence.  Even more than a decade after the end of the cold war we have enough nuclear ICBM to blow the crap out of ourselves anyway; so what's the difference if we were to do it by dropping MIRVs on each other?  The only really constructive use of nuclear weapons (the 10 or so major powers currently have the conventional forces to ensure their interests - nukes are only really useful to upstart dictatorships which want to blackmail the major powers) is to defend earth as a whole against external threats - and to do that you need weapons batteries pointing outwards.<br>
<br>
Really, if the countries capable of space-based weapons systems were willing to &quot;play fair&quot;, they could honour a treaty that continues to ban any weapon that points back at Earth.  You could, for instance, design space-based nukes in an unaerodynamic fashion so that they would burn up high in Earth's atmosphere and do no more than, at best, create an EMP pulse - this would make the weapons useless for causing major destruction on the surface, although they could damage unshielded electronics.  Furthermore, under UN (or some other body's) supervision, you could have code written into the flight control software of these systems which refuses to accept any trajectory aiming back at earth.  Of course the various participants in the system would probably try to leave hidden &quot;back doors&quot; for themselves in the code, but you could at least try to get agreement.<br>
<br>
Another factor about using nukes to deflect or destroy a planet-killer is that ours aren't nearly powerful enough.  In the opinions of the various nuclear experts here, could we build a 10 000 megaton hydrogen bomb (as opposed to about 100 megatons, which is where I believe we maxed out - correct me if I'm wrong)?  Would it be economically feasible to build such a thing? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 2060<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/18/03 11:35 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=23.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/zaphod3.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: UN and asteroid defence</span><hr size=1> There was some discussion in a previous thread that stated the max yield tested was something on the order of 50+ megatons by the Soviet Union.<br>
<br>
The Project Orion book talked about the idea of a continent buster nuke that could be delivered by a deep space patrol Orion, the weapon weighing something on the order of 1,650 tons... but the problem after a certain megaton size is that all you end up doing is blowing a hole through the atmosphere and not much more.  The earth's curvature helps in reducing the amount of damage done to it's surface by the nuclear blast.<br>
<br>
An Orion would make a good defense against an impending asteroid impact.  The best use would be course correction of the offending rock at the earliest time. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NS Administrator</span><br>  Posts: 944<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/19/03 10:04 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=23.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: UN and asteroid defence</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Really, if the countries capable of space-based weapons systems were willing to &quot;play fair&quot;, they could honour a treaty that continues to ban any weapon that points back at Earth.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
It's not good how willing the political establishment is to just blanket ban everything and overlook the positives of nuclear explosives.  I see the seeds of the same irrational fear of nuclear technology being sown in the nanotech field.  I read at least once a week an article that demands we halt all nanotech research on the basis that nanotech could be turned into a horrible weapon and abused.  They just don't see the very immense positives that adv. nanotech could provide.  We'll never move forward into the universe or a better world if we hold on to our fear of everything powerful. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=markix@nuclearspace>MarkIX</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 14<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/19/03 10:10 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=23.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Fear Kills</span><hr size=1> it kills enjoyment, happiness, contentment, confidence self-esteem and trust without these things life becomes very bad and thats when fear can kill you.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=captainbeowulf>CaptainBeowulf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 18<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/20/03 3:10 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=23.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Nanotech</span><hr size=1> What are luddites on against nanotech for now?  Is this the old &quot;grey ooze&quot; theory - that you could build a swarm of nannites which would eat everything that exists?  This is kind of like saying back in the 1960's that we shouldn't develop the microchip because it may mean that HAL could become possible one day... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NS Administrator</span><br>  Posts: 952<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/20/03 10:50 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=23.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Nanotech</span><hr size=1> Actually, that gray ooze theory pops up a lot.  Among the fears I've been reading is that some our nanotech will multiply out of control and consume everything in its path, or that nanotech will create asbestos like particles that won't dissolve in the lung, or that it will lead to the creation of Star Trek like synthesizers that will allow anyone to build whatever they want, like nuke bombs and wreak havoc on society.  The list goes on and on, but I think nanotech will end up like cloning or nukes, you can ban it in some countries, but you can't ban it in all of them and for that reason alone I think we should accelerate our research so as not to be caught with our pants down.   Environmentalists especially seem to be taking a vehement stance against nanotech development.  People like John Bell, Rifkin, etc, are convinced nanotech will hurt the environment, but I believe just the opposite is true.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mylenejenius@nuclearspace>MyleneJenius</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 51<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/22/03 5:04 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=23.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.csclub.uwaterloo.ca/u/yhchan/gallery/mylene/thumbnail/Mac704.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/leela1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Nanotech</span><hr size=1> Hai... the ubiquitous fear of what MIGHT happen. As a general rule I ignore their fearful diatribes unless they can quote any scientific edidence (make that REAL scientific evidence... not what they wish was real).<br>
